passages.text: AFL | Ollie's Bargain Outlet Holdings (Matthew R. Boss, CPA) (OLLI, OW, PT \(\) 159.00\$

OLLI reported 2Q adj. EPS of \(\) 0.99\(above Street\) \ \(0.92\) ) comprised of \(+5.0\%\) same- store sales or a \(10.8\%\) 2- year stack ( \(>\) Street at \(+1.7\%\) ) and gross margin expansion of \(+206\) bps Y/Y to \(39.9\%\) (above Street at \(39.1\%\) ) translating to \(21\%\) gross profit dollar growth (doubling the model's \(\sim 10\%\) TTM average). Looking ahead, management raised the FY25 EPS outlook to \(\) 3.76- 3.84\((vs.\) \ \(3.65 - 3.75\) prior and Street \(\) 3.76\() based on \(+3.0 - 3.5\%\) SSS (vs \(+1.4 - 2.2\%\) prior), 85 net new stores ( \(= 15\%\) unit growth vs. 75 prior), gross margin \(\sim 40.3\%\) ( \(>\) historical algo / vs. prior \(\sim 40.0\%\) ), and \(11.2\%\) margin at the midpoint (vs 11.0- 11.2% prior guide and Street at \(11.2\%\) ).
The Gap, Inc. (Matthew R. Boss, CPA) (GAP, OW, PT \(\) 32.00\$
4 Key Incremental CFO Follow- Up Takeaways:

(1) July Comp Inflection To Close 2Q . . . Breaking down the cadence of 2Q's \(+1.0\%\) comp growth, CFO O'Connell noted May/June started slow due to unfavorably cold/wet weather weighing on core seasonal merchandise ( \(=\) Flat May/June consolidated SSS by our work), relative to a sharp acceleration to mid-single-digit comps in July on our estimates, coinciding w the Fall product drop and back-to-school assortment flowed through to stores.
Oil Markets Weekly (Natasha Kaneva)
Tariffs on India kick inâ€”Russian oil flows likely to continue at limited discounts
Despite higher tariffs, India continues to buy Russian crude at reduced levels, a trend likely to persist until a trade deal is finalized and Russia maintains discounts

Russia has successfully redirected the 0.5 mbd drop in Indian exports but is unlikely to offer discounts beyond the current \(\) 2.60\$ /bbl, preferring to cut production over providing the deep discounts seen in 2022
Daily Economic Briefing (Maia G Crook)

The second release of US 2Q25 GDP delivered an upward revision to a \(3.3\%\) gain. The material upward revision to domestic final sales growth (from \(1.1\%\) or to \(1.6\%\) ) was concentrated in nonresidential business investment, where every category was revised up. The slowing in equipment spending gains from 1Q25 has moderated, with gains now at a \(7.4\%\) . Intellectual property product spending was notably weak last year, rising just \(2.7\%\) , but with today's upward revision it is now up a \(9.3\%\) or in 1H25. This rebound can principally be attributed to a \(22\%\) or rise in software spending in 1H25, which likely in part reflects earnings from selling AI software services.
